  "Question": "<p>The problem:</p> <blockquote> <p>Defining <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_950\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\sin x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </math></span> as the leg <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_951\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"b\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>b</mi> </math></span> of a right triangle with <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_952\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\angle B=x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2220</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>B</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </math></span> (in radians) and hypotenuse <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_953\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mn>1</mn> </math></span>, prove that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_954\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\lim_{x\\to 0}\\frac{\\sin x}{x}=1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <munder> <mo movablelimits=\"false\">lim</mo> <mrow> <mi>x</mi> <mo>\u2192</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </munder> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> <mi>x</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span></p> </blockquote> <p>(The motivation is to find the derivative of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_955\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\sin x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </math></span> in a elementary, \"pre-Taylor\" and \"pre-series\" context).</p> <p>I have seen many times a proof that it is based in the fact that the length of the arc <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_956\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>x</mi> </math></span> satisfies <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_957\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?><math alttext=\"\\sin x&amp;lt;x&amp;lt;\\tan x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo>\u2061</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mrow></math></span> or sometimes <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_958\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?><math alttext=\"\\sin x&amp;lt;x&amp;lt;\\sin x+1-\\cos x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo>\u2061</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>&lt;</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo>-</mo><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow></math></span> The lower bound is clear because the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_959\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\sin x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </math></span> is the length of a straight segment and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_960\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>x</mi> </math></span> is the length of a curved segment with the same endpoints. But I find that the upper bound is based on this intuitive fact:</p> <blockquote> <p>If <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_961\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"F\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>F</mi> </math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_962\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"G\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>G</mi> </math></span> are two convex subsets of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_963\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\Bbb R^{2}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\Bbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msup> <mi>R</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math></span> and   <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_964\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"F\\subset G\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>F</mi> <mo>\u2282</mo> <mi>G</mi> </mrow> </math></span>, then <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_965\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?><math alttext=\"|\\partial F|&amp;lt;|\\partial G|\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><mo>\u2202</mo><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow><mo>&lt;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo><mrow><mo>\u2202</mo><mo>\u2061</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span>.</p> </blockquote> <p>(<span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_966\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"|\\partial F|\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo> <mrow> <mo>\u2202</mo> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>F</mi> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">|</mo> </mrow> </math></span> is the length of the boundary of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_967\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"F\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>F</mi> </math></span>).</p> <p>But I haven't ever seen a proof of that. I tried it myself but I get stuck trying to bound <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_968\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\int_{s}^{t}\\sqrt{1+y^{\\prime}(u)^{2}}du\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <msubsup> <mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u222b</mo> <mi>s</mi> <mi>t</mi> </msubsup> <mrow> <msqrt> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mi>y</mi> <mo>\u2032</mo> </msup> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msup> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>u</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </msqrt> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo>\ud835\udc51</mo> <mi>u</mi> </mrow> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> provided for example that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_969\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"y^{\\prime\\prime}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <msup> <mi>y</mi> <mi>\u2032\u2032</mi> </msup> </math></span> is negative and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_970\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"y(s)=y(t)\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>y</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>s</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mi>y</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>t</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span>. I realize that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_971\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"y^{\\prime}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <msup> <mi>y</mi> <mo>\u2032</mo> </msup> </math></span> can't be bounded (note for example <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_972\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"y=\\sqrt{1-x^{2}}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>y</mi> <mo>=</mo> <msqrt> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mo>-</mo> <msup> <mi>x</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </msqrt> </mrow> </math></span>, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_973\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"-1\\leq x\\leq 1\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mo>\u2264</mo> <mi>x</mi> <mo>\u2264</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span>).</p> <p><strong>Question</strong></p> <p>Is it possible to justify the derivative of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_974\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\sin x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </math></span> or the inequality about the lengths of bounds? Is there any calculus text with this approach (or similar) to define trigonometical functions?</p>",
  "Title": "Length of convex paths and bounding <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_949\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\sin x\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>sin</mi> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> </math></span>",
